title The dec jet -- fast, slow, and dispatched, proven to agree
prompt kg
think Weighed the two doors I had named as "genuinely new design territory" (a Hoon-to-Nock compiler front end, or a jet/acceleration layer) rather than treating "kg" as license to attempt either blindly. Chose the jet layer: meaningfully more scoped than a full compiler front end, and already named concretely in the original TAME-supplement scoping study ("every jet in Glow ships with a paired witness -- a fixture proving the accelerated path and the pure Glow path produce identical output on the same input").
think Chose dec (decrement) as the first jet for the same reason real Hoon education materials do: Nock has a native increment (opcode 4) but no native decrement at all, so computing dec purely in Nock genuinely requires a real, slow, recursive computation -- not a toy example, an honest one.
think Designed the slow path as a real self-recursive Nock core, composed from opcodes already proven across laps 1-3 (6 for the test, 7 to compose building-the-core with invoking-it, 9 to invoke the arm, 10 to edit the running counter into a fresh core each iteration) -- exactly the shape Hoon's own |- trap desugars to, built here from raw opcodes with no rune, no parser, no shortcut.
think Traced the whole algorithm by hand against a concrete case (dec(3)) before writing the witness, and caught a real logic error in my own first draft this way: the loop's own termination test needs to compare n against b+1, not against b directly (the classic off-by-one a naive "count up to n" reading invites) -- caught by hand-tracing rather than by a failed run, which would have silently returned dec(3)=3 instead of 2.
think Built the slow formula to take the bare atom n as ITS OWN subject (via an opening autocons that constructs the initial core [arm [n 0]] from n alone), rather than requiring a pre-built core handed in -- so the same formula can sit under a jet-dispatching opcode-11 hint and be evaluated with a plain atom subject, matching how a real jetted gate call would actually be shaped.
think Extended eval() with a small, explicit jet-dispatch function (not folded into nock_core.rye's own opcode-11 case, keeping the base interpreter jet-agnostic) that recognizes one specific hint tag and substitutes the fast native path, falling through to the ordinary slow evaluation for any other tag -- proving both the substitution and the fallback in the same witness, rather than only the happy path.
think Anticipated, rather than discovered by crash, a genuine question the depth-bounded interpreter raises for real recursion: how many dec-loop iterations does max_depth=64 actually support? Rather than guess or assert a number, wrote the witness to MEASURE the honest limit directly (probing n=1..20, recording the largest that still completes), landing on n=10 -- and named the finding plainly as a real, informative limit rather than a defect to quietly patch around.
think Proved dec(0)'s own two honest refusals rather than treating it as an edge case to skip: the fast path names DecrementOfZero directly (no natural predecessor); the slow path, if actually run, would loop forever (no b ever satisfies n = b+1 when n is 0) -- and the SAME depth bound that measures the honest n=10..20 limit above also catches this real non-termination cleanly, turning what would be an infinite loop in unbounded Nock into a clean DepthExceeded refusal. Named this as a genuine demonstration of why the bound exists, not only a theoretical safety net.
think Hit the now-familiar `test` reserved-keyword trap a third time this session (once in lap 2, now here) -- renamed on sight without needing to search for the fix, the pattern having become recognized rather than merely remembered.
obs This lap's own honest depth-limit finding (n=10 under max_depth=64) is real, useful information about this interpreter as it stands today, not a flaw to hide: a bounded interpreter with no tail-call elimination will always have SOME such limit, and naming it precisely, by measurement, is exactly the kind of claim this whole session's own discipline has tried to keep -- checkable rather than asserted.
obs Both design doors I was weighing this turn were named, by me, as needing a check-in before attempting -- yet the jet layer turned out to be genuinely tractable within a single "kg" continuation, once properly scoped down to one real jet rather than a general system. Worth naming as a pattern: "needs its own design pass" and "too big for one continuation" are not always the same judgment, and separating them mattered here.
file nock/nock_jet_dec.rye new -- slow_dec_formula() (hand-built self-recursive core), fast_dec() (native), eval_with_dec_jet() (dispatch + fallthrough)
file nock/nock_jet_dec_witness.rye new -- seven claims: fast/slow agreement across inputs, dec(0)'s two honest refusals, dispatch proven by comparison, fallthrough proven unchanged, and the depth limit measured rather than guessed
file nock/JET_DEC.md new -- names the jet's own obligation (fast is only ever a faster spelling of an already-proven slow answer) and the honest depth-limit finding
file tools/nock_jet_dec_witness.rish new Rishi wrapper, wired into tools/parity_ch01.rish
file tools/glow_riscv_target_witness.rish extended from eight to nine keystone pieces with the dec jet, cross-built and confirmed byte-identical including the measured depth-limit claim
file nock/README.md a new section pointing to JET_DEC.md; keystone-piece count updated to nine
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md checked line for the dec jet; Last-updated re-stamped
file work-in-progress/ROADMAP.md the Keystone section's "Aligned direction" paragraph reconciled a fifth time -- the jet-layer door named as horizon two turns ago is now itself closed and witnessed
recommend check-in remains for M1, B3, and the TAME-supplement seating, unchanged. The one still-open door in this whole Nock/riscv64/rune/jet thread is a Hoon-to-Nock compiler front end -- named honestly, twice now, as genuinely bigger than a single lap and worth its own design conversation before starting, not a candidate for another direct "kg" continuation.
